elements.content: Two mononuclear seven-coordinated macrocycle manganese­(II) compounds and four polycyanometallates containing different cyanide groups have been employed as building blocks to assemble cyanide-bridged heterobimetallic complexes, resulting in eight cyanide-bridged FeIII/II-MnII and MIV-MnII (M = Mo, W) complexes {[Mn­(L1)]­[Fe­(1-MeIm)­(CN)5]} n (1), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]­[Fe­(1-MeIm)­(CN)5]}­·2H2O (2), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[Fe­(CN)6]} n ­·n(CH4O)­·3.5nH2O (3), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[Fe­(CN)6]}­·11H2O (4), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[Mo­(CN)8]} n ­·4nH2O (5), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[Mo­(CN)8]}­·3.5H2O (6), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[W­(CN)8]} n ­·5nH2O (7), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[W­(CN)8]}­·3H2O (8). (L1 = 3,6-diazaoctane-1,8-diamine, L2 = 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine). Single X-ray analysis reveals that complexes 1, 3, 5, and 7 obtained by using [Mn­(L1)]2+ as assemble segment can be structurally characterized as a one-dimensional coordination polymer, while the structures of the complexes 2, 4, 6, and 8 with [Mn­(L2)]2+ as the ancillary compound belong to polynuclear entities, indicating that the different coordination field of the N atom or the O atom in the macrocyclic ligands can have an obvious influence on the structure types of the target complexes. Investigation of magnetic properties of complexes 1 and 2 showed the antiferromangetic coupling between the cyanide-bridged low-spin Fe­(III) ion and Mn­(II) ion. Additional, the weak magnetic interaction between the Mn­(II) ions bridged by diamagnetic cyanide building blocks can be found in other complexes.

Introduction

Because molecule-based magnetic materials can provide fundamental insight into interesting magnetic phenomena and are with potential application in magnetic devices, the molecular magnetism has always been a frontier research area during the past decade. Among which, due to the excellent magnetic transferring ability between the paramagnetic metal centers and the comparatively easy prediction of the magnetic coupling nature mediated by the cyanide bridge, the cyanide-bridged magnetic complexes have been given intense attention in the molecular magnetism field, and such intention has also led to much progress in this field. Up to now, a great deal of cyanide-bridged magnetic compounds with diversified molecular topological structures and interesting magnetic properties, such as high-temperature magnetic order, photoresponsive properties, spin-crossover (SCO), chirality, single-molecule magnets (SMMs), and single-chain magnets (SCMs), have been reported.

elements.content: Recently, low-dimensional cyanide-bridged complexes have been actively studied for the purpose of clearly elucidating magneto-structural correlation and preparing interesting molecular materials such as SMMs and SCMs. Generally, the rational design of the cyanide-bridged magnetic materials with low dimensionality can be achieved following a building-block approach with the premeditated association of various complexes and the blocked cyanidometallates [M­(L) x (CN) y ] z− (L = mono- or multi-dentate organic ligand). As have been found from the previous results, several factors such as the number and position of cyanide group, number and nature of charge of cyanide-containing building block, and steric effect of reactants have been used to tune the structure of the cyanide-bridged complexes formed. On the other hand, the ancillary ligands attached to the counterpart assembling cations also play a crucial role in constructing cyanide-bridged complexes with different structures. The polyaza macrocyclic ligands with some rigid character obtained by condensation of 2,6-diacetylpyridine and polyamine, which are usually coordinated to the equatorial plane of metal ions with only two trans replaceable sites weakly bonded to other ligands, have been proven to be good ancillary ligands to assemble low-dimensional structural cyanide-bridged complexes. By incorporating 3d paramagnetic metal ions Mn­(II), Co­(II), Fe­(II), Fe­(III), Ni­(II), etc. into these types of macrocyclic ligands, a few low-dimensional magnetic complexes with interesting magnetic properties have been synthesized. Interested also in these types of ligands, we investigated the reactions of the Mn­(II) compounds based on the two notable macrocyclic ligands with high structural similarity () with four polycyanometallates containing five, six, or eight cyanide groups () and interestingly found that the [Mn­(L1)]2+ (L1 = 3,6-diazaoctane-1,8-diamine) is inclined to form cyanide-bridged one-dimensional (1D) infinite structure, while [Mn­(L2)]2+ (L2 = 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine) is more favorable for constructing a polynuclear entity. Eight 1D or polynuclear cyanide-bridged heterobimetallic complexes with the formula {[Mn­(L1)]­[Fe­(1-MeIm)­(CN)5]} n (1), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]­[Fe­(1-MeIm)­(CN)5]}­·2H2O (2), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[Fe­(CN)6]} n ­·n(CH4O)­·3.5nH2O (3), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[Fe­(CN)6]}­·11H2O (4), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[Mo­(CN)8]} n ­·4nH2O (5), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[Mo­(CN)8]}­·3.5H2O (6), {[Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]­[Mn­(L1)]­[W­(CN)8]} n ­·5nH2O (7), {[Mn­(L2)­(H2O)]2]­[W­(CN)8]}­·3H2O (8), including their synthesis, crystal structures, and magnetic properties, will be described in this paper. The obtained results here provide clear information that the slightly difference from the coordination field of the auxiliary ligand can obviously affect the structure type of the cyanide-bridged complex.

These four complexes were prepared using one similar three layer diffusion procedure; therefore, only the synthesis of 1 was detailed as a typical representative. The structures were solved by direct method and expanded using Fourier difference techniques with the SHELXTL-97 program package. The non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically, while hydrogen atoms were introduced as fixed contributors. All the nonhydrogen atoms except the disordered ones were refined with anisotropic displacement coefficients. For the disordered imidazole molecule in complex 1 and some solvent contents, the partially occupied atoms were refined isotropically. Hydrogen atoms were assigned isotropic displacement coefficients U(H) = 1.2U(C) or 1.5U(C), and their coordinates were allowed to ride on their respective carbons using SHELXL97 except some of the H atoms of the solvent molecules. For these H atoms, they were refined isotropically with fixed U values, and the DFIX command was used to rationalize the bond parameter. These data can be obtained free of charge from the Cambridge Crystallographic Data Centre via www.ccdc.cam.ac.uk/data_request/cif. X-ray Data Collection and Structure Refinement

Single crystals of all the complexes for X-ray diffraction analysis with suitable dimensions were mounted on the glass rod, and the crystal data were collected on a Bruker SMART CCD diffractometer with a Mo Kα sealed tube (λ = 0.71073 Å) using a ω scan mode. The structures were solved by direct method and expanded using Fourier difference techniques with the SHELXTL-97 program package. The non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically, while hydrogen atoms were introduced as fixed contributors. All the nonhydrogen atoms except the disordered ones were refined with anisotropic displacement coefficients. For the disordered imidazole molecule in complex 1 and some solvent contents, the partially occupied atoms were refined isotropically. Hydrogen atoms were assigned isotropic displacement coefficients U(H) = 1.2U(C) or 1.5U(C), and their coordinates were allowed to ride on their respective carbons using SHELXL97 except some of the H atoms of the solvent molecules. For these H atoms, they were refined isotropically with fixed U values, and the DFIX command was used to rationalize the bond parameter. CCDC 1481481-1481488 for complexes 1-8 contain the supplementary crystallographic data for this paper. These data can be obtained free of charge from the Cambridge Crystallographic Data Centre via www.ccdc.cam.ac.uk/data_request/cif. The 15-membered pentadentate macrocycles L1 and L2 (L1 = 3,6-diazaoctane-1,8-diamine, L2 = 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine) ligands presented in adapting a planar conformation with very similar structure can impose a pentagonal-based geometry on the central metal ion, resulting in the stabilization of seven-coordinated species. With some difference from other manganese­(II) complexes based-on aliphatic amines ligands, in which the Mn­(II) ion can be easily oxidized to Mn­(III) ion, the seven-coordinated Mn­(II) species obtained by incorporating Mn­(II) ion into these two macrocyclic ligands are very robust and can be handled in air and in aqueous solution without being oxidized. Furthermore, the large steric effect from the macrocyclic ligand on the equatorial direction can effectively lower the dimensionality of the complexes formed, thus far more favoring of constructing functional complexes with low dimensional structure through replacing the two weakly bonded and replaceable ligands at the two trans positions.

Results and Discussion

Synthesis and General Characterization

The 15-membered pentadentate macrocycles L1 and L2 (L1 = 3,6-diazaoctane-1,8-diamine, L2 = 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine) ligands presented in  adapting a planar conformation with very similar structure can impose a pentagonal-based geometry on the central metal ion, resulting in the stabilization of seven-coordinated species. With some difference from other manganese(II) complexes based-on aliphatic amines ligands, in which the Mn(II) ion can be easily oxidized to Mn(III) ion, the seven-coordinated Mn(II) species obtained by incorporating Mn(II) ion into these two macrocyclic ligands are very robust and can be handled in air and in aqueous solution without being oxidized. Furthermore, the large steric effect from the macrocyclic ligand on the equatorial direction can effectively lower the dimensionality of the complexes formed, thus far more favoring of constructing functional complexes with low dimensional structure through replacing the two weakly bonded and replaceable ligands at the two trans positions.

elements.content: Four cyanide precursors [Mg­(1-CH3im)2­(H2O)2­Fe­(CN)5­(1-CH3im)], K4[Fe­(CN)6], and K4[M­(CN)8] (M = Mo, W) have been used as building blocks to construct cyanide-bridged complexes by assembling with the above two seven-coordinated Mn­(II) compounds. Interestingly, four 1D polymers and four polynuclear entities have been obtained from the reactions of the four polycyanometallates with [Mn­(L1)­(H2O)­Cl]­ClO4 and [Mn­(L2)­(H2O)­Cl]­ClO4, respectively, giving clear information that the coordination field of the N atom or the O atom of the macrocyclic ligand plays an important role to the structural types of the target cyanide-bridged complexes. All the cyanide-bridged heterometallic complexes have been characterized by IR spectroscopy. In the IR spectra of 1–8, two sharp peaks due to the cyanide-stretching vibration were observed at about 2130 and 2160 cm–1, respectively, indicating the presence of bridging and nonbridging cyanide ligands in these complexes.

elements.content: Complexes 1 and 2, which crystallize in monoclinic space group C2/c and orthorhombic space group Pbca, belong to cyanide-bridged neutral 1D infinite structure comprised of repeating [-NC-Fe­(1-MeIm)­(CN)3)-CN-Mn­(L1)-] units and binuclear Fe–Mn entity, respectively. In complex 1, the pentacyanometallate, acting as a bidentate ligand through its two cyanide groups in trans- position, connects the Mn­(II) ion of two independent macrocyclic units, therefore forming a 1D infinite structure. For complex 2, the cyanide-precursor acts as only a monodentate ligand to link one Mn­(II) macrocyclic unit, resulting in a neutral binuclear structure. The Fe atom in these two complexes is involved in a slightly distorted octahedral geometry, for which the six vertexes are coordinated by five C atoms of the cyanide groups and one N atom of the attached substituted imidazole molecule.

In complex 1, the pentacyanometallate, acting as a bidentate ligand through its two cyanide groups in trans- position, connects the Mn(II) ion of two independent macrocyclic units, therefore forming a 1D infinite structure. For complex 2, the cyanide-precursor acts as only a monodentate ligand to link one Mn(II) macrocyclic unit, resulting in a neutral binuclear structure. elements.content: The Mn­(II) ion in both of these two complexes is seven-coordinated, forming a pentagonal-bipyrimidal coordination geometry, in which the five equatorial positions are occupied by N5 or N3O2 unit coming from the macrocyclic ligand. For the additional two axial sites, they are completed by two N atoms of cyanide groups and one cyanide N atom and one solvent O atom in complexes 1 and 2, respectively. The average Mn–N/Oequatorial bond lengths in these two complexes are 2.237 and 2.256 Å, respectively, basically consistent with the Mn–Ncyanide/Oaxial bond length with the values 2.252(5) and 2.239 Å, indicating the comparatively regular pentagonal-bipyrimidal around the Mn­(II) ion. With comparison to the bond angle of Ncyanide–Mn–Ncyanide/Owater distributed in a very narrow range of 172.2(2)–177.04(16)°, the Mn–CN bond angle in complexes 1 and 2 is somewhat bent with the values only of 151.3(5) and 156.9(15)°, demonstrating that these three atoms deviate obviously from a good linear configuration. The intramolecular FeIII–MnII separation through bridging cyanide(s) in these two complexes are 5.117 and 5.230 Å, while the shortest intermolecular metal–metal distance of 8.082 and 8.102 Å is obviously longer than this value. With the help of the intermolecular O–H···O and O–H···N hydrogen bond interactions between the solvent molecules and the cyanide-bridged moiety, complex 2 can be linked into two-dimensional supramolecular structure (Figure S2, Supporting Information).

elements.content: Complexes 3 and 4 present a 1D chain and a trinuclear FeMn2 structure, respectively ( and ). The negative linear chain of complex 3 is comprised by the alternative cyanide precursor and the macrocyclic manganese unit with the two charges balanced by the additional [Mn­(L1)­(H2O)]2+ cation hanging out of the chain alternately. The [Fe­(CN)6]4– ion linked two [Mn­(L1)]2+ cations in the independent unit of the complex 3 by using two cyanide groups in a cis position, while the two Mn­(II) macrocyclic units in complex 4 were connected to the cyanide precursor through the two cyanide bridges in a trans position, indicating that the different coordination donor atoms (N or O) can put an obvious influence on the coordination mode of the cyanide-precursor to the metal atom. Because of the O atoms occupying the axial coordination position of the Mn­(II) ion, it is impossible for these two complexes to assemble into supramolecular structures with higher dimensionality or infinite chain. As tabulated in Table S2 (Supporting Information), all the bond parameters around the Mn­(II) ion are comparable to those found in complexes 1 and 2, giving information that the different cyanide building block has no obvious influence on the pentagonal-bipyrimidal coordination sphere of the Mn­(II) ion. It should be pointed out that, depending on the intermolecular H-bond interactions, these two complexes can be constructed into a 3D and 2D supramolecular structure (Figures S3 and S4, Supporting Information), respectively.

elements.content: The χm T value of complexes 1 and 2 at room temperature is about 4.61 emu K mol–1, which is slightly lower than the spin only value of 4.75 emu K mol–1 for uncoupled Mn­(II) (S = 5/2) and low spin Fe­(III) (S = 1/2) based on g = 2.00. With decreasing the temperature, the χm T value decreases smoothly and attains the value of 4.47 emu K mol–1 for 1 and 4.50 emu K mol–1 for 2 at about 50 K, respectively. After this, the χm T value for complex 1 starts to decrease sharply and reaches its lowest peak with the value about 3.21 emu K mol–1 at 2 K. For complex 2, after also the lowest value is reached with a high decreasing speed from about 50 K, the χm T value further shows an increase with the temperature down to 2 K. A similar magnetic behavior has also been observed in previously reported cyanide-bridged Fe­(III)–Mn­(II) complexes also based on the same macrocyclic manganese compounds. The magnetic susceptibilities for these two complexes conform well to Curie–Weiss law in the range of 2–300 K and give the negative Weiss constant and Curie constant. These data, in combination with the changing tendency of χm T–T, lead to a primary conclusion that the magnetic coupling between Fe­(III) and Mn­(II) bridged by cyanide group in these two complexes is antiferromagnetic.

Therefore, complex 1 can be considered as a chain containing alternating spins 1/2 and 5/2 with only one exchange interaction J (). In this case, the magnetic susceptibility of the infinite chain can be simulated and calculated rationally based on a closed ring cluster model consisting of four pairs of 1/2–5/2 spin pairs. elements.content: The fact that there usually exist antiferromagnetic interaction in the cyanide-bridged low-spin Fe­(III) ion and Mn­(II) ion system is understandable by taking into account the electron configuration of the magnetic orbitals of the above two metal ions. With the magnetic orbitals of low spin Fe­(III) (t2g 5eg 0) and high spin Mn­(II) (t2g 3eg 2) considered, both ferro- and antiferromagnetic contributions can be involved in the magnetic coupling between these two spin magnetic centers. However, the net overlap of the magnetic orbitals through the t2g-t2g pathways, which can result in antiferromagnetic coupling, can usually overwhelm the ferromagnetic term of the t2g-eg orthogonal coupling. As a result, the antiferromagnetic coupling between the low spin Fe­(III) and high spin Mn­(II) is always dominant in cyanide-bridged FeIII–MnII complexes. Additional, the slight variation of J value to some extent in this system can be attributed to the slight structure difference such as the coordination surroundings around the Mn­(II) ion, the bond bending of Mn–NC–Fe linkages, and the Mn–Ncyanide bond distance, etc.

elements.content: In summary, by using polycyanometallates containing five, six, or eight cyanide groups as building blocks and two seven-coordinated macrocyclic Mn­(II) compounds with very high structural similarity as assemble segments, a series of eight cyanide-bridged heterobimetallic complexes structurally characterized as polynuclear clusters or 1D infinite polymer have been synthesized. The structural analysis indicates that the macrocyclic manganese compound based on 3,6-diazaoctano-1,8-diamine is more inclined to form a cyanide-bridged infinite structure when assembling with polydentate cyanide precursors, while, interestingly, the another macrocyclic manganese compound based-on 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine is more favor of constructing polynuclear cyanide-bridged clusters under the same reaction conditions the former used. Investigation over the magnetic properties reveals an overall antiferromagnetic interaction between Fe­(III) and Mn­(II) ions bridged by cyanide group. The present work will be helpful for providing valuable information for the rational design and synthesis of cyanide-bridged magnetic complexes with the different dimensionality and structure type with the slightly different coordination field considered.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusion

In summary, by using polycyanometallates containing five, six, or eight cyanide groups as building blocks and two seven-coordinated macrocyclic Mn(II) compounds with very high structural similarity as assemble segments, a series of eight cyanide-bridged heterobimetallic complexes structurally characterized as polynuclear clusters or 1D infinite polymer have been synthesized. The structural analysis indicates that the macrocyclic manganese compound based on 3,6-diazaoctano-1,8-diamine is more inclined to form a cyanide-bridged infinite structure when assembling with polydentate cyanide precursors, while, interestingly, the another macrocyclic manganese compound based-on 3,6-dioxaoctano-1,8-diamine is more favor of constructing polynuclear cyanide-bridged clusters under the same reaction conditions the former used. Investigation over the magnetic properties reveals an overall antiferromagnetic interaction between Fe(III) and Mn(II) ions bridged by cyanide group. The present work will be helpful for providing valuable information for the rational design and synthesis of cyanide-bridged magnetic complexes with the different dimensionality and structure type with the slightly different coordination field considered.

Synthesis of Complexes <bold>1</bold>–<bold>4</bold>

These four complexes were prepared using one similar three layer diffusion procedure; therefore, only the synthesis of 1 was detailed as a typical representative.
